        <prj:TechnicalJustification>
            <prj:justificationText>We identified the torus emission to be related with a narrow spectral feature in the line profile of NaCl 21-20, with a FWHM of ~6km/s. However, if 
this torus is actually a disk extending from inner regions, we might expect it to present a complex velocity field due to the keplerian rotation. A high 
spectral resolution is mandatory to be able to resolve posible extra components. 
The number of spectral resolutions per line with is ~75.

We also will covered the upper band with a low resolution wide bandwith spectral setup. These observations will allow us to probe the continuum as 
well as to observe several HCN vibrationally excited lines and the emission from SiS 15-14, HNC 3-2, HC3N 30-29 and Al37Cl 19-18. 
</prj:justificationText>
            <prj:justificationKey>ED_CORRELATOR</prj:justificationKey>
        </prj:TechnicalJustification>
        <prj:TechnicalJustification>
            <prj:justificationText>The torus observed around IRC+10216 in Cycle O is the closest observed towars an evolved star.
This proximity makes this torus the best source to study the properties of the disks around evolved stars, which are believed to be fundamental to 
power the outflows observed in the post-AGB phase.
Therefore, we aim to map this emission with a very high angular resolution to resolve the density and velocity changes along this disk, as well as to 
be able to detect the presence of an infall in the innermost regions towards the star. In particular, we ask for a spatial resolution of 0.05", which is slightly 
larger than the stellar diameter (0.04"). This spatial resolution would allow us to trace any molecular emission just above the star.</prj:justificationText>
            <prj:justificationKey>ED_ANGULAR_RESOLUTION</prj:justificationKey>
        </prj:TechnicalJustification>
        <prj:TechnicalJustification>
            <prj:justificationText>We aimed to map the emission arising from a slow expanding and rotating torus around IRC+10216. In order to resolve all the components of this 
torus, we aim to obtain a rms of 10 mJy/beam. 
The rms level has been estimated from the expected NaCl 21-20 emission from radiative transfer modeling of the previous Cycle O observations and single dish data (Quintana-Lacaci et al. submitted). See also Fig.4 of the current proposal. 


Since the emission from the torus is very compact in velocities we ask for a high spectral resolution of 0.08 km/s. In addition to this, we propose to 
use a baseband of the spectral setup to properly observe the continuum at the proposed frequency.

</prj:justificationText>
            <prj:justificationKey>ED_SENSITIVITY</prj:justificationKey>
        </prj:TechnicalJustification>
        <prj:TechnicalJustification>
            <prj:justificationText>Since the polarisation of the selected lines is negligible, we ask for single polarisation in order to optimize the frequency resolution of the spectral 
setup.</prj:justificationText>
            <prj:justificationKey>ED_SINGLE_POLARISATION</prj:justificationKey>
        </prj:TechnicalJustification>
