    <prp:abstract>Recenty ALMA Cycle O - Band 6 observations revealed the presence of a rotating torus rich in NaCl, KCl and their isotopologues in IRC+10216. This rotating torus is the closest observed towards an evolved star.  However, the angular and spectral resolution of these observations were not enought to resolve neither the structure nor the velocity field. 

This torus can be related with a dust lane observed in IR images, which has also been related with a bipolar outflow observed in the innermost regions of the ejecta of IRC+10216.

We aim to observe the NaCl J=21-20 emission line, which is most intense NaCl transition in Band 6, with an angular resolution of 0.05" and a spectral resolution of 0.08 km/s. This will allow us to perform a deep study the structure and kinematics of this torus, and to constrain the origin of this torus not observed in other molecules but in salts.  In addition, a detailed study of the kinematics could resolve the presence of infalls which might power the outflows observed. 
</prp:abstract>
